==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Epigram
<hw>Ep"i*gram</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>epigramma</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ inscription, epigram, fr. <?/ to write
upon, <grk>'epi`</grk> upon + <?/ to write: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧pigramme</ets>. See <er>Graphic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A short poem treating concisely and pointedly of a single thought
or event. The modern epigram is so contrived as to surprise the reader
with a witticism or ingenious turn of thought, and is often satirical in
character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dost thou think I care for a satire or an <qex>epigram</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Epigrams</xex> were originally inscription on
tombs, statues, temples, triumphal arches, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An effusion of wit; a bright thought tersely and
sharply expressed, whether in verse or prose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The style of the epigram.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Antithesis, <it>i. e</it>., bilateral stroke, is the soul of
<qex>epigram</qex> in its later and technical signification.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Cracroft.</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>Epigrammatical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Epigrammatic</ent>⟦br⟧
